This paper deals with optimization problems and algorithms, which are typically studied in computer science. The use of dependent rounding and correlation properties suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-categories of cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) and cs.LG (machine learning). The mention of budget constraints and optimization also suggests the sub-category of cs.AI (artificial intelligence). The paper also deals with approximation algorithms, which are often studied in the sub-category of cs.GT (computational complexity and game theory) and the use of algorithms to handle small subsets of variables suggests the sub-category of cs.DM (discrete mathematics).
